<br>
If evade fails 30% of the time under optimal conditions, then we will be able to strip off roughly 7% of our total current hate every ten seconds.  Without the actual details of how hate is built, I would suspect that that will buy us a few seconds of bliss.<br>
<br>
If we do the math, this is what this means:<br>
<br>
Let us make some assumptions:<br>
<br>
Rogue hate built per 10 seconds:  500<br>
Rogue evade effectiveness when NOT under attack: 70%<br>
<br>
When you run the numbers, you find out that there is an effective max hate you can generate on a mob if you are constantly evading.  <br>
<br>
You reach that number *much* quicker (obviously) with a 33% decline in hate (original proposal) than you do with a 10% decline in hate (new proposal).<br>
<br>
So much quicker that out of all the proposals, I *really* prefer the first.  I hate to lose the guaranteed switch of evade, but I'd rather get to the &quot;safe zone&quot; faster.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.kabald.org/hategraph.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
With a 33% reduction (modified by the 70% chance of evade), you reach your hate plateau in about 2 minutes.  <br>
<br>
With a 10% reduction (modified by the 70% chance of evade), you reach your hate plateau in about 10 minutes.<br>
<br>
In either case, basically, at the beginning of a fight, you build hate *fast* and need to be very careful.  By the end of the fight, screw it, the reduction per evade in hate will be exactly equal to the hate you produce.<br>
<br>
(Note that the amount of hate you actually build up every 10 seconds is irrelevant.)<br>
<br>
--Latro Abiectus<br>
